  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks aimed at combating money laundering. The primary global body that sets standards in this area is the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**. Established in 1989, the FATF is an intergovernmental organization that develops policies to combat money laundering, terrorist financing, and other threats to the integrity of the international financial system.\n\n### Key International Frameworks and Laws:\n\n1. **FATF Recommendations**:  \n   The FATF's **40 Recommendations** provide a comprehensive framework for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CTF). These recommendations are widely adopted by countries around the world and serve as the global standard for AML/CTF efforts.\n\n2. **United Nations Conventions**:  \n   - The **UN Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)** (Vienna Convention) was one of the first international agreements to criminalize money laundering.\n   - The **UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)** (Palermo Convention) also includes provisions against money laundering.\n   - The **UN Convention against Corruption (2003)** (Merida Convention) requires states to establish AML measures and cooperate internationally.\n\n3. **European Union Directives**:  \n   The EU has issued several anti-money laundering directives (AMLD) to harmonize AML laws across its member states. The most recent is the **6th Anti-Money Laundering Directive (AMLD6)**, which strengthens AML measures and extends criminal liability.\n\n4. **Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**:  \n   The Basel Committee has issued principles and guidelines for banks to prevent their services from being used for money laundering.\n\n5. **Egmont Group of Financial Intelligence Units**:  \n   This international network facilitates cooperation and information sharing among national Financial Intelligence Units (FIUs) to combat money laundering.\n\n### Implementation in National Laws:  \nCountries are expected to incorporate these international standards into their national laws. For example, the U.S. has the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Patriot Act**, while the UK has the **Proceeds of Crime Act (POCA)** and the **Money Laundering Regulations**.\n\n### Enforcement and Peer Reviews:  \nThe FATF conducts mutual evaluations of member countries to assess their compliance with AML standards. Non-compliant countries may be placed on the FATF's \"grey list\" or \"blacklist,\" which can lead to financial sanctions and other consequences.\n\n### Conclusion:  \nInternational laws against money laundering are robust and continually evolving to address new threats, such as **cryptocurrency laundering** and other emerging risks. Countries are expected to implement these standards to protect the global financial system.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
